&lt;div class="post-text" itemprop="text"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is called a one-to-many relationship. You have one shape and many actual points. You would usually want to put the points into a separate table, like this.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;+----------------------+      +-----------------+
|        Shape         |      |  Point_Values   |
+----------------------+      +-----------------+
| shape_id (INT)       |      | shape_id (INT)  |
| shape_name (VARCHAR) |      | point_x (INT)   |
+----------------------+      | point_y (INT)   |
                              +-----------------+
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To make a new shape, insert a new shape into the &lt;code&gt;Shape&lt;/code&gt; table. Then create one or more values in the &lt;code&gt;Point_Values&lt;/code&gt; table. When you want to go back and get the values, you would use a join, like this:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;SELECT s.shape_name, v.point_x, v.point_y
FROM Shape s
JOIN Point_Values v ON s.shape_id = v.shape_id
WHERE s.shape_id = 5
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This has the advantage of being very flexible. Each shape can have 0 or more points, and there is an implicit enforcement that there must be an equal number of x and y points.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

